      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Does anyone here understand the nature of capital punishment in China? The majority of people executed in China are not murderers. China executes people for non-violent crimes like embezzlement and corruption in political office. They also execute a lot of political prisoners. You can be executed in China for things that wouldn't even get you arrested in the US.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;In China, the State takes ownership of the bodies of executed prisoners. The deceased family is not allowed to claim the body. The State disposes of them as they see fit.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I can imagine a scenario where a condemmed prisoner is held on "death row" until such time as someone needs a new liver, or heart.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Order comes in for a type B Positive liver and the warden goes thru his list of inmates to decide who's going to die today....&lt;/P&gt;</description>
