      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Science fiction predicts again...&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Larry Niven had a lot to say about organs being &amp;quot;harvested&amp;quot; from criminals. In a short story (I can't remember what it was called), minor offences such as driving through a red light are capital crimes so that the organ banks which feed the insatiable demand for body parts can be kept full.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;He also has some stories about &amp;quot;organlegging&amp;quot; in the &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://sites.inka.de/~W3775/reviews/Flatlander.html"&gt;Gil Hamilton series&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;One of his early novels was &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.fantasybookspot.com/node/1052"&gt;A Gift from Earth&lt;/a&gt;. Not great, but I liked some of the ideas in it, particularly the way in which the gift itself meant the end of capital punishment.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Cordwainer Smith wrote a story called &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Planet_Named_Shayol"&gt;A Planet Named Shayol&lt;/a&gt; Criminals are sent to a planet where they live forever, but they grow extra organs which are harvested from them &lt;em&gt;in vivo&lt;/em&gt; while they are under the effects of a powerful narcotic. I love this story, but I am at a loss to understand why.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
